.Dd July 8, 2026
.Dt TEETAP 1
.Os "teetap 0.1.2"
.Sh NAME
.Nm teetap
.Nd detachable, tee-based local log tap for agents and humans
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Cm run
.Op Fl d
.Op Fl -rotate | -truncate | -split
.Ar name
.Fl -
.Ar command
.Op Ar args ...
.Nm
.Cm pipe
.Ar name
.Nm
.Cm stop
.Op Fl t Ar seconds
.Ar name
.Nm
.Cm pm2 link
.Op Ar name-filter ...
.Nm
.Cm path
.Nm
.Cm status
.Nm
.Cm list
.Nm
.Cm flush
.Op Fl -older-than Ar age
.Op Fl -all
.Op Ar name ...
.Nm
.Cm off
.Op Fl -force
.Nm
.Cm skill install
.Op Fl -allow-fetch
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility captures the output of local processes to one well-known directory
per project, outside the repository, so that coding agents and other
observers can read it with
.Xr tail 1
and
.Xr grep 1
without owning the process.
It is runtime-agnostic: it moves bytes and does not care what produced them.
.Pp
Each project (git worktree) gets its own directory under the aggregate root
(default
.Pa ~/.local/state/teetap ) ,
keyed by the toplevel's basename and a hash of its absolute path.
Because captures live outside the repository, branching, committing, and
conflict resolution never interact with them.
.Pp
The following commands are available:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Cm run Oo Fl d Oc Oo Fl -rotate | -truncate | -split Oc Ar name Fl - Ar command Op Ar args ...
Run
.Ar command
with stderr merged into stdout, teeing output to
.Ar name Ns Pa .log
in the project directory while passing it through to the terminal.
The wrapped command's exit code is recorded in the session end marker and
propagated as the exit status of
.Nm .
By default output is appended;
.Fl -rotate
moves the existing log to
.Ar name Ns Pa .prev.log
first,
.Fl -truncate
clobbers it in place, and
.Fl -split
writes a new
.Ar name . Ns Ar session-id Ns Pa .log
per run.
.Pp
With
.Fl d
.Pq or Fl -detach ,
start
.Ar command
detached and return immediately, printing its pid and log path instead of
streaming; the terminal is free and closing it does not end the capture.
Session markers are still written, including the end marker with the exit
code when the command later exits, crashes, or is stopped.
A name whose detached command is still running is refused.
Detached commands are started and stopped, never supervised: nothing
restarts on crash and no health is monitored.
To detach a producer that would otherwise be piped, wrap it instead:
.Dl teetap run -d pod -- kubectl logs -f pod
.It Cm pipe Ar name
Act as a sink: read standard input, stamp a session start marker, append
through
.Xr tee 1
to
.Ar name Ns Pa .log
while passing the stream to standard output, and stamp an end marker on
end-of-file.
Use it to tap producers that cannot be wrapped: pipelines, remote tails,
container logs.
.It Cm stop Oo Fl t Ar seconds Oc Ar name
End a detached tap started with
.Cm run Fl d :
send SIGTERM to the command, wait up to
.Ar seconds
.Pq default 10
for it to exit, then send SIGKILL.
The session end marker records the resulting exit code.
Stopping a name that is not running is not an error.
.It Cm pm2 link Op Ar name-filter ...
Symlink PM2's existing log files into the project directory with a
.Dq pm2-
filename prefix.
All log files by default, or only those whose names match a given filter.
Idempotent: re-running adds new files and prunes dead links.
Output is never re-piped or duplicated.
.It Cm path
Print the project directory for the current working directory.
This is the single authority for the naming convention; scripts and agents
should use it rather than deriving paths themselves.
.It Cm status
List each source in this project's directory as NAME, TYPE, BYTES, and
AGE_S (seconds since last write).
TYPE is
.Dq run
while a detached command is alive,
.Dq tee
for other capture files, and
.Dq link
for symlinked sources.
An age near zero means the source is actively writing.
.It Cm list
List every tapped project under the aggregate root as PROJECT, PATH (the
source directory recorded when the project was first tapped), SOURCES, and
AGE_S, most recently active first.
Use it to find logs for a project that was tapped from a different working
directory.
.It Cm flush Oo Fl -older-than Ar age Oc Oo Fl -all Oc Op Ar name ...
Delete capture files.
Without arguments, delete all capture files in the current project.
With
.Ar name
arguments, delete only named files.
With
.Fl -older-than ,
keep files whose last modification is more recent than
.Ar age
(format:
.Dq 30m ,
.Dq 6h ,
.Dq 7d ) .
With
.Fl -all ,
sweep every project under the aggregate root instead of just the
current one.
Filters combine:
.Dl teetap flush --older-than 6h dev api
deletes
.Pa dev.log
and
.Pa api.log
only if stale.
.Pp
Symlinks (PM2 links) are never touched.
Files with a live detached process are always skipped with a pointer to
.Cm stop .
The project directory and
.Pa .teetap-project
breadcrumb survive, so the project remains plugged in.
.It Cm off Op Fl -force
Detach: remove all symlinks unconditionally (targets are untouched) and
delete capture files, except files written within the last 10 seconds,
which are treated as live and skipped with a warning unless
.Fl -force
is given.
.Cm off
never ends processes: a tap whose detached command is still running is
always skipped — even with
.Fl -force
— with a pointer to
.Cm stop .
.It Cm skill install Op Fl -allow-fetch
Install the agent skill to the skills directory (default
.Pa ~/.claude/skills/teetap )
so coding agents know how to find and query the logs.
The recommended onboarding is the skills.sh ecosystem:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
npx skills add https://github.com/weefaa/teetap --skill teetap
.Ed
.Pp
.Nm Cm skill install
is the no-Node fallback.
It is offline by default: it copies the skill bundled next to the script
(repository checkout), or writes the SKILL.md embedded in the binary
itself, version-locked to this release.
With
.Fl -allow-fetch
it downloads the full skill structure from this binary's own release tag
in a single tarball.
.El
.Sh SESSION MARKERS
Every capture session is bracketed in the log file by marker lines:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
===== teetap session <id> start <time> name=<n> branch=<b> cwd=<c> pid=<p> =====
===== teetap session <id> end <time> name=<n> exit=<code> =====
.Ed
.Pp
Readers should scope to the text after the last start marker to see only
the current run.
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width TEETAP_SKILLS_DIR
.It Ev TEETAP_DIR
Aggregate root.
Default:
.Pa ~/.local/state/teetap .
.It Ev TEETAP_PM2_LOGS
PM2 log directory.
Default:
.Pa ~/.pm2/logs .
.It Ev TEETAP_SKILLS_DIR
Agent skills directory.
Default:
.Pa ~/.claude/skills .
.It Ev TEETAP_REPO
GitHub repository used when fetching the skill standalone.
Default:
.Li weefaa/teetap .
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Pa ~/.local/state/teetap/<project>-<hash>/
Per-project log directory: real files from captures, symlinks from sources.
.It Pa <project-dir>/.teetap-project
Breadcrumb recording the project's source path; written on first tap,
preserved by
.Cm off ,
read by
.Cm list .
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It 0
Success, including the no-op cases where nothing is tapped.
.It 1
Operational error: PM2 log directory not found, skill fetch failed, or
unknown command.
.It 2
Usage error: missing or malformed arguments.
.El
.Pp
.Cm run
exits with the wrapped command's own exit status.
.Sh EXAMPLES
Tap a dev server (any runtime) and watch it live from another terminal:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ teetap run dev -- npm run dev
$ tail -f "$(teetap path)"/dev.log
.Ed
.Pp
Tap a stream that cannot be wrapped:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ kubectl logs -f mypod | teetap pipe mypod
.Ed
.Pp
Find logs for a project tapped from another directory:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ teetap list
.Ed
.Pp
Query the aggregate like a log store:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ grep -h "<request-id>" "$(teetap path)"/*.log
$ sed -n '/13:18:00/,/13:18:30/p' "$(teetap path)"/dev.log
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr grep 1 ,
.Xr sed 1 ,
.Xr tail 1 ,
.Xr tee 1
